    "plan_content": "Here's a summary of the plan I've written:\n\n---\n\n## Plan: `next/geo` Utility Module\n\n**5 files total** — 4 new, 1 modified. All follow the exact patterns of `next/server` / `user-agent.ts`.\n\n### What gets created\n\n| File | Role |\n|------|------|\n| `packages/next/src/server/web/spec-extension/geo.ts` | Core implementation (mirrors `user-agent.ts`) |\n| `packages/next/geo.js` | CJS public entry (mirrors `server.js`) |\n| `packages/next/geo.d.ts` | Type declarations (mirrors `server.d.ts`) |\n| `packages/next/package.json` | Add `\"geo.js\"`, `\"geo.d.ts\"` to `files` after `form.d.ts` |\n| `packages/next/src/server/web/spec-extension/geo.test.ts` | Jest tests — 10 cases |\n\n### Key implementation notes\n\n- **`geo.ts`**: `Headers.get()` returns `string | null`, so every field uses `?? undefined` to strip nulls (required for `strict: true`). Vercel headers take priority over `cf-ipcountry` for `countryCode`. `country` is derived by looking up `countryCode` in a typed `Record<string, string>` map. Haversine formula for `geoDistance`.\n- **`geo.js`**: Aggregation object + `module.exports` + individual `exports.X` — identical structure to `server.js`.\n- **`geo.d.ts`**: `export type { Geo }` (interface = type-only), plain `export` for all four functions. Hand-authored, excluded from TS compilation by existing `\"./*.d.ts\"` rule in `tsconfig.json`.\n- **Tests**: Cover all 4 exported functions including CF fallback, case-insensitive region matching, missing headers → `undefined`, and NY→London distance within ±50 km.",
